- ts: 2026-05-06T18:16:13Z
  event: clarify_critic
  feature: lifecycle-adopts-cortex-resolve-backlog-item-delete-refine-references-clarifymd
  parent_epic_loaded: true
  findings:
    - text: "Intent clarity HIGH overstates clarity because Phase 1 explicitly authorizes a forked outcome — 'decide per-case whether refine's helper produces correct behavior or whether the helper needs an enhancement to preserve lifecycle's match semantics.' The intent is therefore not 'one outcome' as the assessment claims; it is at least two outcomes contingent on test results."
      origin: primary
    - text: "Intent clarity HIGH treats the audit pressure-test 'NOT NO-OP' framing as authoritative without flagging that the ticket does not enumerate a single concrete input where lifecycle and refine resolve differently. The semantic delta is asserted, not demonstrated."
      origin: primary
    - text: "Scope boundedness HIGH leans on touch-point enumeration but Phase 1 explicitly contemplates enhancing 'bin/cortex-resolve-backlog-item' while the touch-points list says '(verify; no changes expected)' — internal contradiction between scope assertions."
      origin: primary
    - text: "Scope boundedness HIGH cites 'specific test inputs listed' but the source provides categories (numeric IDs, kebab slugs, etc.), not enumerated cases, and verification 'New contract test passes for all curated input cases' is circular since curation is itself part of the work."
      origin: primary
    - text: "Requirements alignment HIGH does not engage with the requirement that simplification preserve behavior. The ticket's own 'adopting refine's flow changes which backlog items resolve unambiguously vs as ambiguous' is a behavioral regression vector that the project simplicity quote does not authorize."
      origin: primary
    - text: "Requirements alignment HIGH was reached after loading only requirements/project.md; no area-level requirements file was checked despite the repo structure noting area-level requirements exist."
      origin: primary
    - text: "Complexity 'complex' is correct in tier but the rationale doesn't engage with downstream-consumer surface for lifecycle's clarify behavior — that surface is not enumerated in the source and the assessment does not flag the gap."
      origin: primary
    - text: "Criticality HIGH is justified as a 'default for skill/workflow infrastructure changes' rather than derived from the source. The source-grounded reasoning ('lifecycle skill is widely used') is also present, but the assessment frames the rating via the rubric default rather than the source."
      origin: primary
    - text: "Parent epic 172 frames the work as a multi-area densification (~700 lines duplication, harness logic, artifact bloat, stale references, copy-paste bug). The child ticket addresses one sub-area, which is normal decomposition, but Phase 1's 'enhance the helper' branch could re-introduce complexity the parent epic is trying to trim — research should evaluate whether helper-enhancement conflicts with the parent's deduplication intent."
      origin: alignment
  dispositions:
    apply: 2
    dismiss: 6
    ask: 1
  applied_fixes:
    - "Revised intent clarity from HIGH to MEDIUM: the high-level intent (lifecycle adopts the helper, refine clarify.md deleted) is unambiguous, but the implementation outcome forks based on Phase 1 empirical findings. Research must produce evidence-backed answers about predicate divergence before Spec can lock in the implementation path."
    - "Recorded alignment consideration for Research: evaluate whether the 'enhance the helper to preserve lifecycle semantics' branch in Phase 1 risks adding back complexity the parent epic 172 is trying to trim. If divergences exist and would force helper enhancement, weigh that complexity addition against the deduplication win."
  dismissals:
    - finding_index: 1
      rationale: "The unknown semantic delta is the work product of Phase 1, not a defect in the intent. A research-shaped intent that names the empirical step is not 'overclaimed clarity'; the ticket is explicit that Phase 1 will demonstrate the delta before any deletion."
    - finding_index: 2
      rationale: "Phase 1 explicitly authorizes helper enhancement ('whether the helper needs an enhancement to preserve lifecycle's match semantics'), so the touch-points line 'verify; no changes expected' is a default expectation, not a constraint. Reading both passages together resolves the apparent contradiction; the touch-points list will be updated during Spec if Phase 1 surfaces required helper changes."
    - finding_index: 3
      rationale: "Test-case curation is a Spec-phase work product, not a Clarify-phase scope ambiguity. The ticket lists the input categories that must be covered; the spec interview (Step 5) will enumerate concrete cases per category."
    - finding_index: 5
      rationale: "Repository requirements/ contains only project.md, multi-agent.md, observability.md, pipeline.md, and remote-access.md. Per project.md's 'Conditional Loading' section, none of those area docs apply to skills/lifecycle/backlog tooling. Loading project.md alone was the correct coverage for this feature."
    - finding_index: 6
      rationale: "Complex is the correct rating. Adding downstream-consumer surface to the rationale would only strengthen the rating, not invalidate it. The simple/complex tier is binary; the rationale richness is a Spec-phase concern."
    - finding_index: 7
      rationale: "The rubric in clarify.md §5 explicitly directs 'Default to high for skill/lifecycle/hook/workflow changes' — the assessment correctly cited that default. The source-grounded reasoning ('lifecycle skill is widely used') was also present, so the rating is doubly supported."
  status: ok
